{{Shrine | Name = Shiogama Shrine | image = [[File:Shiogama_jinja(Shinbashi,_Minato)_01.jpg|240px]] | Location = {{ill|Minato, Tokyo|ja|港区 (東京都)|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tokyo|ja|東京都|12=draft|12=draft}} | Coordinates = {{WikidataCoord|display=inline,title}} | Deity = {{ill|Shiotsuchi no Oji|ja|シオツチノオジ|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|武甕槌命|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Futsunushi no Kami|ja|経津主命|12=draft|12=draft}} | Founded = {{ill|Genroku|ja|元禄|12=draft|12=draft}} 8 ({{ill|1695|ja|1695th year|12=draft|12=draft}}) }}
'''Shiogama Shrine''' (鹽竈神社, Shiogama Jinja) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Minato, Tokyo|ja|港区|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tokyo|ja|東京都|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Overview == In {{ill|1695|ja|1695th year|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Genroku|ja|元禄|12=draft|12=draft}} 8), {{ill|Date Tsunamura|ja|伊達綱村|12=draft|12=draft}}, the {{ill|daimyō|ja|藩主|12=draft|12=draft}} of {{ill|Sendai Domain|ja|仙台藩|12=draft|12=draft}}, enshrined a {{ill|divided spirit|ja|分霊|12=draft|12=draft}} from the {{ill|Shiogama Shrine|ja|鹽竈神社|12=draft|12=draft}} in his domain and established the shrine within the {{ill|Edo upper residence|ja|江戸上屋敷|12=draft|12=draft}} of the Sendai Domain in {{ill|Shiodome|ja|汐留|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="Historical Walk">Motoaki Tawara, "Minato-ku Historical Walk (Tokyo Historical Guide 3)," Gakuseisha, 1992, pp. 29-30</ref>.
In {{ill|1856|ja|1856年|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Ansei|ja|安政|12=draft|12=draft}} 3), the shrine was relocated to the {{ill|Sendai Domain Edo Middle Residence|ja|仙台藩江戸中屋敷|12=draft|12=draft}}, its current location, and opened for public worship. Even after the departure of the Sendai Domain officials in the {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, the shrine continued to be revered as a deity of safe childbirth<ref name="Historical Walk"></ref>.
The shrine grounds were formerly part of the Sendai Domain's Edo residence and were owned by the Date family. In {{ill|1930|ja|1930th year|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Shōwa|ja|昭和|12=draft|12=draft}} 5), in response to local requests, the then-head of the Date family, {{ill|Date Okimune|ja|伊達興宗|12=draft|12=draft}}, donated the land to the local {{ill|neighborhood association|ja|町内会|12=draft|12=draft}}, "Atago-shita Neighborhood Association." The area was subsequently opened as "Shiogama Park," Tokyo’s only park managed by a neighborhood association. In {{ill|1972|ja|1972nd year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Shōwa 47), the park was transferred to the administration of Minato Ward<ref name="Minato-ku">[https://www.city.minato.tokyo.jp/shisetsu/koen/shiba/06.html Shiogama Park] Minato-ku Shiba Area Comprehensive Office, Urban Development Division</ref>.
== Access == * A 5-minute walk from {{ill|Onarimon Station|ja|御成門駅|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{OSM route map|start=35.66125,139.75173|goal=35.66321,139.75433|name=Route Guide}}).
