'''Shiogama Shrine''' (鹽竈神社, Shiogama Jinja) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in {{ill|Minato, Tokyo|ja|港区|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minato, Tokyo|qq=}}, {{ill|Tokyo|ja|東京都|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokyo|qq=}}.
== Overview == In {{ill|1695|ja|1695年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1695|qq=}} ({{ill|Genroku|ja|元禄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Genroku|qq=}} 8), {{ill|Date Tsunamura|ja|伊達綱村|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Date Tsunamura|qq=}}, the {{ill|daimyō|ja|藩主|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/daimyō|qq=}} of {{ill|Sendai Domain|ja|仙台藩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sendai Domain|qq=}}, enshrined a {{ill|divided spirit|ja|分霊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/divided spirit|qq=}} from the {{ill|Shiogama Shrine|ja|鹽竈神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiogama Shrine|qq=}} in his domain and established the shrine within the {{ill|Edo upper residence|ja|江戸上屋敷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo upper residence|qq=}} of the Sendai Domain in {{ill|Shiodome|ja|汐留|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiodome|qq=}}<ref name="Historical Walk">Motoaki Tawara, "Minato-ku Historical Walk (Tokyo Historical Guide 3)," Gakuseisha, 1992, pp. 29-30</ref>.
In {{ill|1856|ja|1856年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1856|qq=}} ({{ill|Ansei|ja|安政|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ansei|qq=}} 3), the shrine was relocated to the {{ill|Sendai Domain Edo Middle Residence|ja|仙台藩江戸中屋敷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sendai Domain Edo Middle Residence|qq=}}, its current location, and opened for public worship. Even after the departure of the Sendai Domain officials in the {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治|lt=Meiji period|1=Meiji era|2=ja|3=明治|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji period|qq=}}, the shrine continued to be revered as a deity of safe childbirth<ref name="Historical Walk"></ref>.
The shrine grounds were formerly part of the Sendai Domain's Edo residence and were owned by the Date family. In {{ill|1930|ja|1930年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1930|qq=}} ({{ill|Shōwa|ja|昭和|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōwa|qq=}} 5), in response to local requests, the then-head of the Date family, {{ill|Date Okimune|ja|伊達興宗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Date Okimune|qq=}}, donated the land to the local {{ill|neighborhood association|ja|町内会|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/neighborhood association|qq=}}, "Atago-shita Neighborhood Association." The area was subsequently opened as "Shiogama Park," Tokyo’s only park managed by a neighborhood association. In {{ill|1972|ja|1972nd year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1972|qq=}} (Shōwa 47), the park was transferred to the administration of Minato Ward<ref name="Minato-ku">[https://www.city.minato.tokyo.jp/shisetsu/koen/shiba/06.html Shiogama Park] Minato-ku Shiba Area Comprehensive Office, Urban Development Division</ref>.
== Access == * A 5-minute walk from {{ill|Onarimon Station|ja|御成門駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onarimon Station|qq=}} ({{OSM route map|start=35.66125,139.75173|goal=35.66321,139.75433|name=Route Guide}}).
